sentences: Alicia "Alice" Armendariz, (born November 7, 1958) known professionally as Alice Bag, is an American punk rock singer, musician, author, educator and feminist archivist.
Bag has remained active in music since the late 1970s and released her second book in 2015.
Bag has remained active in music since the late 1970s and released her second book in 2015.
She released Alice Bag, her debut solo album on Don Giovanni Records in June 2016.
A second solo album, Blueprint, was released in 2018.
As a member of the punk rock band the Bags, Alice was at the forefront of the L.A. punk rock scene in the late 1970s.
Throughout her years of gaining her education, Bag experienced not so friendly encounters and was picked on.
During her middle school and high school years, she was picked on for her weight, her teeth, and her physical appearance.
Members of the Bags appeared as the Alice Bag Band in director Penelope Spheeris's landmark 1981 documentary on the Southern California punk scene, The Decline of Western Civilization.
Still today Alice shares her music with her followers.
The Bags were active from year 1977–1981.

She has her full album of Stay at Home Bomb, Cholita!, and all songs she has previously recorded.
In 2016 Alice Bag released her debut solo album, Alice Bag, on punk label Don Giovanni Records.

A second album, Blueprint, followed in early 2018 and featured numerous guest musicians including Allison Wolfe and Kathleen Hanna who sang on the track "77" which refers to the unequal pay that women receive for the same work as men.
In 2020 another album, entitled Sister Dynamite, was released by In the Red Records on April 24, 2020.
In 2020 another album, entitled Sister Dynamite, was released by In the Red Records on April 24, 2020.
Bag's memoir, Violence Girl, From East LA Rage to Hollywood Stage – A Chicana Punk Story, was published by Feral House in fall 2011.
In 2008, Bag attended a comic-con with her daughter, and that is where her initial inspiration to create Violence Girl came from.

Since 2004, Bag has also maintained a digital archive of interviews with women who were involved in the first wave of the Southern California punk scene in the 1970s, including musicians, writers, and photographers.

Continuing her movement in empowering women, Bag was the keynote speaker at the 2012 Women Who Rock: Making Scenes Building Communities unConference in Seattle, Washington.

Bag currently maintains part-time residency in Los Angeles, California and Phoenix, Arizona.
She has recently begun exhibiting her oil paintings in gallery showings.
